Threat Hunting > [T3]: Endpoint Hunting for Persistence

Persistence refers to an attacker's ability to maintain control over a compromised system, even after the initial intrusion has been discovered and remediated. In this lesson, we will focus on hunting for persistence using scheduled tasks as an example.

In this lesson, we will cover:

  • Methods attackers use to achieve persistence
  • Detecting persistence using scheduled tasks
  • Analyzing data in Kibana to identify anomalies

 

Methods Attackers Use to Achieve Persistence

Attackers can achieve persistence in various ways, including:

  • Creating backdoors: Installing a backdoor on a compromised system, allowing the attacker to regain access even after the initial intrusion has been discovered and remediated.
  • Installing malicious services: Installing a malicious service on a compromised system, ensuring persistence even after a system restart.
  • Task scheduling: Creating scheduled tasks that run a malicious payload at regular intervals, ensuring the attacker retains control over the system even after a reboot.
  • Modifying system settings: Modifying system settings or registry keys to ensure that malicious code is executed whenever the system starts up.

 

Detecting Persistence Using Scheduled Tasks

One way to detect persistence is by monitoring scheduled tasks for signs of malicious activity. For example, you can use Kibana to analyze event data collected by Sysmon, focusing on event ID 13 and the rule name "technique_id=T1053,technique_name=Scheduled Task." This will help you identify any potentially malicious scheduled tasks that have been created by an attacker to maintain persistence.

 

Analyzing Data in Kibana to Identify Anomalies

To spot anomalies and identify potentially malicious scheduled tasks, you can use Kibana's visualizations to analyze the data. Look for rare registry paths or unusual patterns of behavior that may indicate a security threat.

You can quickly identify unfamiliar scheduled tasks by searching the task name on Google. This will help determine if it's a recognized task or if it requires a more in-depth investigation
